# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: high-speed-serdes
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:high-speed-serdes/10b-encoding] In telecommunications, **8b/10b** is a line code that maps 8-bit words to 10-bit symbols to achieve DC balance and bounded disparity, and at the same time provide enough state changes to allow reasonable clock recovery.
[src:high-speed-serdes/10b-encoding] This means that the difference between the counts of ones and zeros in a string of *at least* 20 bits is no more than two, and that there are not more than five ones or zeros in a row.
[src:high-speed-serdes/10b-encoding] This helps to reduce the demand for the lower bandwidth limit of the channel necessary to transfer the signal.
[src:high-speed-serdes/10b-encoding] An 8b/10b code can be implemented in various ways with focus on different performance parameters.
[src:high-speed-serdes/10b-encoding] Odaka for the DAT digital audio recorder.
[src:high-speed-serdes/10b-encoding] Kees Schouhamer Immink designed an 8b/10b code for the DCC audio recorder.
[src:high-speed-serdes/10b-encoding] The IBM implementation was described in 1983 by Al Widmer and Peter Franaszek.
[src:high-speed-serdes/10b-encoding] As the scheme name suggests, eight bits of data are transmitted as a 10-bit entity called a *symbol*, or *character*.
[src:high-speed-serdes/10b-encoding] The low five bits of data are encoded into a 6-bit group (the 5b/6b portion) and the top three bits are encoded into a 4-bit group (the 3b/4b portion).
[src:high-speed-serdes/10b-encoding] These code groups are concatenated together to form the 10-bit symbol that is transmitted on the wire.
[src:high-speed-serdes/10b-encoding] The *data symbols* are often referred to as D.x.y where x ranges over 0–31 and y over 0–7.
[src:high-speed-serdes/10b-encoding] Standards using the 8b/10b encoding also define up to 12 *special symbols* (or *control characters*) that can be sent in place of a *data symbol*.
[src:high-speed-serdes/10b-encoding] They are often used to indicate start-of-frame, end-of-frame, link idle, skip and similar link-level conditions.
[src:high-speed-serdes/10b-encoding] At least one of them (i.e. a "comma" symbol) needs to be used to define the alignment of the 10-bit symbols.
[src:high-speed-serdes/10b-encoding] They are referred to as K.x.y and have different encodings from any of the D.x.y symbols.
[src:high-speed-serdes/10b-encoding] Because 8b/10b encoding uses 10-bit symbols to encode 8-bit words, some of the possible 1024 (10 bit, 210) symbols can be excluded to grant a run-length limit of 5 consecutive equal bits and to ensure the difference between the count of zeros and ones to be no more than two.
[src:high-speed-serdes/10b-encoding] Some of the 256 possible 8-bit words can be encoded in two different ways.
[src:high-speed-serdes/10b-encoding] Using these alternative encodings, the scheme is able to achieve long-term DC-balance in the serial data stream.
[src:high-speed-serdes/10b-encoding] This permits the data stream to be transmitted through a channel with a high-pass characteristic, for example Ethernet's transformer-coupled unshielded twisted pair or optical receivers using automatic gain control.
[src:high-speed-serdes/10b-encoding] Note that in the following tables, for each input byte (represented as `HGF EDCBA`), *A* denotes the least significant bit (LSB), and *H* the most significant (MSB).
[src:high-speed-serdes/10b-encoding] The output gains two extra bits, **i** and **j**.
[src:high-speed-serdes/10b-encoding] The bits are sent from LSB to MSB: a, b, c, d, e, **i**, f, g, h, and **j**; i.e., the 5b/6b code followed by the 3b/4b code.
[src:high-speed-serdes/10b-encoding] This ensures the uniqueness of the special bit sequence in the comma symbols.
[src:high-speed-serdes/10b-encoding] The residual effect on the stream to the number of zero and one bits transmitted is maintained as the *running disparity* (*RD*) and the effect of slew is balanced by the choice of encoding for following symbols.
[src:high-speed-serdes/10b-encoding] The 5b/6b code is a paired disparity code, and so is the 3b/4b code.
[src:high-speed-serdes/10b-encoding] Each 6- or 4-bit code word has either equal numbers of zeros and ones (a disparity of zero), or comes in a pair of forms, one with two more zeros than ones (four zeros and two ones, or three zeros and one one, respectively) and one with two less.
[src:high-speed-serdes/10b-encoding] When a 6- or 4-bit code is used that has a non-zero disparity (count of ones minus count of zeros; i.e., −2 or +2), the choice of positive or negative disparity encodings must be the one that toggles the running disparity.
[src:high-speed-serdes/10b-encoding] In other words, the non zero disparity codes alternate.
[src:high-speed-serdes/10b-encoding] 8b/10b coding is DC-free, meaning that the long-term ratio of ones and zeros transmitted is exactly 50%.
[src:high-speed-serdes/10b-encoding] To achieve this, the difference between the number of ones transmitted and the number of zeros transmitted is always limited to ±2, and at the end of each symbol, it is either +1 or −1.
[src:high-speed-serdes/10b-encoding] This difference is known as the *running disparity* (RD).
[src:high-speed-serdes/10b-encoding] This scheme needs only two states for the running disparity of +1 and −1.
[src:high-speed-serdes/10b-encoding] For each 5b/6b and 3b/4b code with an unequal number of ones and zeros, there are two bit patterns that can be used to transmit it: one with two more "1" bits, and one with all bits inverted and thus two more zeros.
[src:high-speed-serdes/10b-encoding] Depending on the current running disparity of the signal, the encoding engine selects which of the two possible six- or four-bit sequences to send for the given data.
[src:high-speed-serdes/10b-encoding] Obviously, if the six-bit or four-bit code has equal numbers of ones and zeros, there is no choice to make, as the disparity would be unchanged, with the exceptions of sub-blocks D.07 (00111) and D.x.3 (011).
[src:high-speed-serdes/10b-encoding] In either case the disparity is still unchanged, but if RD is positive when D.07 is encountered 000111 is used, and if it is negative 111000 is used.
[src:high-speed-serdes/10b-encoding] Likewise, if RD is positive when D.x.3 is encountered 0011 is used, and if it is negative 1100 is used.
[src:high-speed-serdes/10b-encoding] This is accurately reflected in the charts below, but is worth making additional mention of as these are the only two sub-blocks with equal numbers of 1s and 0s that each have two possible encodings.
[src:high-speed-serdes/10b-encoding] † For D.x.7, either the Primary (D.x.P7), or the Alternate (D.x.A7) encoding must be selected in order to avoid a run of five consecutive 0s or 1s when combined with the preceding 5b/6b code.
[src:high-speed-serdes/10b-encoding] Sequences of exactly five identical bits are used in comma symbols for synchronization issues.
[src:high-speed-serdes/10b-encoding] With *x* = 23, *x* = 27, *x* = 29, and *x* = 30, the 3b/4b code portion used for control symbols K.x.7 is the same as that for D.x.A7.
[src:high-speed-serdes/10b-encoding] Any other D.x.A7 code can't be used as it would result in chances for misaligned comma sequences.
[src:high-speed-serdes/10b-encoding] ‡ Only K.28.1, K.28.5, and K.28.7 generate comma symbols, that contain a bit sequence of five 0s or 1s.
[src:high-speed-serdes/10b-encoding] The control symbols within 8b/10b are 10b symbols that are valid sequences of bits (no more than six 1s or 0s) but do not have a corresponding 8b data byte.
[src:high-speed-serdes/10b-encoding] They are used for low-level control functions.
[src:high-speed-serdes/10b-encoding] For instance, in Fibre Channel, K28.5 is used at the beginning of four-byte sequences (called "Ordered Sets") that perform functions such as Loop Arbitration, Fill Words, Link Resets, etc.
[src:high-speed-serdes/10b-encoding] Comma symbols are used for synchronization (finding the alignment of the 8b/10b codes within a bit-stream).
[src:high-speed-serdes/10b-encoding] If K.28.7 is not used, the unique comma sequences 00**11111**0 or 11**00000**1 cannot inadvertently appear at any bit position within any combination of normal codes.
[src:high-speed-serdes/10b-encoding] ‡ If K.28.7 is allowed in the actual coding, a more complex definition of the synchronization pattern than suggested by † needs to be used, as a combination of K.28.7 with several other codes forms a false misaligned comma symbol overlapping the two codes.
[src:high-speed-serdes/10b-encoding] A sequence of multiple K.28.7 codes is not allowable in any case, as this would result in undetectable misaligned comma symbols.
[src:high-speed-serdes/10b-encoding] K.28.7 is the only comma symbol that cannot be the result of a single bit error in the data stream.
[src:high-speed-serdes/10b-encoding] After the above-mentioned IBM patent expired, the scheme became even more popular and was chosen as a DC-free line code for several communication technologies.
[src:high-speed-serdes/10b-encoding] The FC-0 standard defines what encoding scheme is to be used (8b/10b or 64b/66b) in a Fibre Channel system – higher speed variants typically use 64b/66b to optimize bandwidth efficiency (since bandwidth overhead is 20% in 8b/10b versus approximately 3% (~ 2/66) in 64b/66b systems).
[src:high-speed-serdes/10b-encoding] Thus, 8b/10b encoding is used for 4GFC and 8GFC variants; for 10GFC and 16GFC variants, it is 64b/66b.
[src:high-speed-serdes/10b-encoding] The Fibre Channel *FC1* data link layer is then responsible for implementing the 8b/10b encoding and decoding of signals.
[src:high-speed-serdes/10b-encoding] The Fibre Channel 8b/10b coding scheme is also used in other telecommunications systems.
[src:high-speed-serdes/10b-encoding] Data is expanded using an algorithm that creates one of two possible 10-bit output values for each input 8-bit value.
[src:high-speed-serdes/10b-encoding] Each 8-bit input value can map either to a 10-bit output value with odd disparity, or to one with even disparity.
[src:high-speed-serdes/10b-encoding] This mapping is usually done at the time when parallel input data is converted into a serial output stream for transmission over a fibre channel link.
[src:high-speed-serdes/10b-encoding] The odd/even selection is done in such a way that a long-term zero disparity between ones and zeroes is maintained.
[src:high-speed-serdes/10b-encoding] The 8-bit to 10-bit conversion scheme uses only 512 of the possible 1024 output values.
[src:high-speed-serdes/10b-encoding] Of the remaining 512 unused output values, most contain either too many ones (or too many zeroes) and therefore are not allowed.
[src:high-speed-serdes/10b-encoding] This still leaves enough spare 10-bit odd+even coding pairs to allow for at least 12 special non-data characters.
[src:high-speed-serdes/10b-encoding] The codes that represent the 256 data values are called the data (D) codes.
[src:high-speed-serdes/10b-encoding] The codes that represent the 12 special non-data characters are called the control (K) codes.
[src:high-speed-serdes/10b-encoding] All of the codes can be described by stating 3 octal values.
[src:high-speed-serdes/10b-encoding] This is done with a naming convention of "Dxx.x" or "Kxx.x".
[src:high-speed-serdes/10b-encoding] Now these bits are converted to decimal in the way they are paired.
[src:high-speed-serdes/10b-encoding] Note that 8b/10b is the encoding scheme, not a specific code.
[src:high-speed-serdes/10b-encoding] While many applications do use the same code, there exist some incompatible implementations; for example, Transition Minimized Differential Signaling, which also expands 8 bits to 10 bits, but it uses a completely different method to do so.
[src:high-speed-serdes/10b-encoding] 64b/66b encoding, introduced for 10 Gigabit Ethernet's 10GBASE-R Physical Medium Dependent (PMD) interfaces, is a lower-overhead alternative to 8b/10b encoding, having a two-bit overhead per 64 bits (instead of eight bits) of encoded data.
[src:high-speed-serdes/10b-encoding] This scheme is considerably different in design from 8b/10b encoding, and does not explicitly guarantee DC balance, short run length, and transition density (these features are achieved statistically via scrambling).
[src:high-speed-serdes/10b-encoding] 64b/66b encoding has been extended to the 128b/130b and 128b/132b encoding variants for PCI Express 3.0 and USB 3.1, respectively, replacing the 8b/10b encoding in earlier revisions of each standard.
[src:high-speed-serdes/66b-encoding] In data networking and transmission, **64b/66b** is a line code that transforms 64-bit data to 66-bit line code to provide enough state changes to allow reasonable clock recovery and alignment of the data stream at the receiver.
[src:high-speed-serdes/66b-encoding] It was defined by the IEEE 802.3 working group as part of the IEEE 802.3ae-2002 amendment which introduced 10 Gbit/s Ethernet.
[src:high-speed-serdes/66b-encoding] At the time 64b/66b was deployed, it allowed 10 Gb Ethernet to be transmitted over fiber optic with the same lasers used by SONET OC-192, rather than requiring the 12.5 Gbit/s lasers that were not expected to be available for several years.
[src:high-speed-serdes/66b-encoding] The protocol overhead of a coding scheme is the ratio of the number of raw payload bits to the number of raw payload bits plus the number of added coding bits.
[src:high-speed-serdes/66b-encoding] The overhead of 64b/66b encoding is 2 coding bits for every 64 payload bits or 3.125%.
[src:high-speed-serdes/66b-encoding] This is a considerable improvement on the 25% overhead of the previously used 8b/10b encoding scheme, which added 2 coding bits to every 8 payload bits.
[src:high-speed-serdes/66b-encoding] The overhead can be reduced further by doubling the payload size to produce the **128b/130b** encoding used by PCIe 3.0.
[src:high-speed-serdes/66b-encoding] As its scheme name suggests, 64 payload bits are encoded as a 66-bit entity.
[src:high-speed-serdes/66b-encoding] The 66-bit entity is made by prefixing one of two possible 2-bit preambles to the 64 payload bits.
[src:high-speed-serdes/66b-encoding] This 66-bit entity is now of two possible states.
[src:high-speed-serdes/66b-encoding] The preambles 002 and 112 are not used and indicate an error if seen.
[src:high-speed-serdes/66b-encoding] The use of the 012 and 102 preambles guarantees a bit transition every 66 bits, which means that a continuous stream of 0s or 1s cannot be valid data.
[src:high-speed-serdes/66b-encoding] It also allows easier clock/timer synchronization, as a transition must be seen every 66 bits.
[src:high-speed-serdes/66b-encoding] The 64-bit payload is then scrambled using a self-synchronous scrambler function.
[src:high-speed-serdes/66b-encoding] Scrambling is not intended to encrypt the data but to ensure that a relatively even distribution of 1s and 0s are found in the transmitted data.
[src:high-speed-serdes/66b-encoding] The scrambler cannot guarantee that output data will never have a long run-length of 0s or all 1s, or other undesirable properties in communications, but does allow strong statistical bounds to be put on the probability of such events.
[src:high-speed-serdes/66b-encoding] Practical designs will choose system parameters such that a bit-error due to long run-lengths is vanishingly unlikely.
[src:high-speed-serdes/66b-encoding] This method is different from the code-book based approach of 8b/10b encoding.
[src:high-speed-serdes/66b-encoding] The encoding and scrambling are normally implemented entirely in hardware, with the scrambler using a linear-feedback shift register.
[src:high-speed-serdes/66b-encoding] Upper layers of the software stack need not be aware that the link layer is using these methods.
[src:high-speed-serdes/66b-encoding] 64b/66b's design goals are clock recovery, stream alignment, DC balance, transition density and run length.
[src:high-speed-serdes/66b-encoding] 8b/10b encoding guarantees strict bounds on DC balance, transition density and run length, whereas 64b/66b provides statistical bounds on these properties.
[src:high-speed-serdes/66b-encoding] Most clock recovery circuits designed for SONET OC-192 and 64b/66b are specified to tolerate an 80-bit run length.
[src:high-speed-serdes/66b-encoding] Such a run cannot occur in 64b/66b because transitions are guaranteed at 66-bit intervals, and in fact long runs are very unlikely.
[src:high-speed-serdes/66b-encoding] Although it is theoretically possible for a random data pattern to align with the scrambler state and produce a long run of 65 zeroes or 65 ones, the probability of such an event is equal to flipping a fair coin and having it come up in the same state 64 times in a row.
[src:high-speed-serdes/66b-encoding] At 10 Gigabits per second, the expected event rate of a 66-bit block with a 65-bit run-length, assuming random data, is 66×264÷1010÷2 seconds, or about once every 1900 years.
[src:high-speed-serdes/66b-encoding] The run length statistics may get worse if the data consists of specifically chosen patterns, instead of being random.
[src:high-speed-serdes/66b-encoding] This vulnerability was kept secret until the scrambler length was increased to 43 bits (RFC 2615 (1999)) making it impossible for a malicious attacker to jam the system with a short sequence.
[src:high-speed-serdes/66b-encoding] 64b/66b avoided this vulnerability by using a scrambling polynomial with enough random internal state (58 bits) so that a dedicated attacker using a crafted Ethernet packet can only create a 64-bit run-length in the scrambler output once in about 29 years.
[src:high-speed-serdes/66b-encoding] This creates 66-bit blocks containing 65-bit runs at a rate similar to using random data.
[src:high-speed-serdes/66b-encoding] The DC balance of 64b/66b is not absolutely bounded.
[src:high-speed-serdes/66b-encoding] However, it can be shown that the scrambler output closely approximates a sequence of random binary bits.
[src:high-speed-serdes/66b-encoding] Passing such a sequence through an AC-coupled circuit produces a baseline wander noise that follows a Gaussian distribution, and the impact on the system error rate can be statistically quantified.
[src:high-speed-serdes/66b-encoding] In practice, a modest coupling capacitor value of 1 nF in a 100 Ω system is sufficient to guarantee that a DC drift of more than 2.5% will occur less often than once per 1022 bits (about 31,700 years at 10 Gbit/s).
[src:high-speed-serdes/66b-encoding] 10 Gigabit Ethernet has a strict charter requiring a Mean Time to False Packet Acceptance (MTTFPA) to be on the order of 1 billion years for a single operating link.
[src:high-speed-serdes/66b-encoding] To achieve this at normal bit error rates requires at least a 4-bit Hamming distance protection for all packet data.
[src:high-speed-serdes/66b-encoding] In other words, all combinations of 3 randomly spaced bit-flips within a packet boundary must be detected and result in an invalidated packet.
[src:high-speed-serdes/66b-encoding] The combination of CRC-32 and the chosen scrambler polynomial were evaluated by exhaustively enumerating all 4-bit error patterns for all possible packet sizes with an optimized C program.
[src:high-speed-serdes/66b-encoding] The main contribution of 64b/66b is the observation that deterministic run length and transition density of 8b/10b are not always worth a 25% code overhead, and that solid robust systems could be designed using statistically bounded methods.
[src:high-speed-serdes/66b-encoding] At some point, practical risks, whether from mean time between failures (MTBF) of components such as power supplies or from phenomena such as cosmic rays or solar flares, dominate the reliability of both 8b/10b and 64b/66b systems.
[src:high-speed-serdes/66b-encoding] The Interlaken protocol improves the DC balance further by trading off more coding bits.
[src:high-speed-serdes/66b-encoding] Its 64b/67b encoding extends 64b/66b with explicit DC balancing.
[src:high-speed-serdes/66b-encoding] This may be beneficial for some applications, such as using smaller on-chip coupling capacitors.
[src:high-speed-serdes/66b-encoding] PCI Express 3.0 introduced 128b/130b encoding, which is similar to 64b/66b but has a payload of 128 bits instead of 64 bits, and uses a different scrambling polynomial: *x*23 + *x*21 + *x*16 + *x*8 + *x*5 + *x*2 + 1.
[src:high-speed-serdes/66b-encoding] It is also not self-synchronous and so requires explicit synchronization of seed values, in contrast with 64b/66b.
[src:high-speed-serdes/66b-encoding] USB 3.1 and DisplayPort 2.0 use 128b/132b encoding, which is identical to 64b/66b, but duplicates each of the preamble bits to reduce the risk of undetected errors there.
[src:high-speed-serdes/66b-encoding] For each {*n*}b/{*n*+2}b encoding, the symbol/data ratio is always below 1.
[src:high-speed-serdes/66b-encoding] With a ratio of 0.985 for 128b/130b encoding, there is no real margin for improvement.
[src:high-speed-serdes/66b-encoding] Very common are 512b/514b encodings combined with Reed–Solomon error correction.
[src:high-speed-serdes/66b-encoding] The FEC allows symbol error rates of 2.3 · 10−5 or 2.2 · 10−4 to achieve a bit error rate of less than 10−15 in the transmitted data.
[src:high-speed-serdes/66b-encoding] Further improvements are possible by switching from PAM-2 to PAM-4 or Ensemble NRZ coding.
[src:high-speed-serdes/clock-recovery] In serial communication data are normally transmitted and received as a series of pulses with well-defined timing constraints.
[src:high-speed-serdes/clock-recovery] In asynchronous serial communication this presents a problem for the receiving side: if their own clock is not precisely synchronized with the transmitter, they may sample the signal at the wrong time and thereby decode the signal incorrectly.
[src:high-speed-serdes/clock-recovery] Partially, the problem may be addressed with extremely accurate and stable clocks, like atomic clocks, but these are expensive and complex.
[src:high-speed-serdes/clock-recovery] More common low-cost clock systems, like quartz oscillators, are accurate enough for this task over short periods of time, but over a period of minutes or hours the clock drift in these systems will make timing too inaccurate for most tasks.
[src:high-speed-serdes/clock-recovery] Clock recovery addresses this problem by embedding clock information into the data stream, allowing the transmitter's clock timing to be determined.
[src:high-speed-serdes/clock-recovery] This normally takes the form of short signals inserted into the data that can be easily seen and then used in a phase-locked loop or similar adjustable oscillator to produce a receiver's clock signal that can be used to time the signal in the periods between the clock signals.
[src:high-speed-serdes/clock-recovery] The advantage of this approach is that a small drift in the transmitter's clock can be compensated as the receiver will always match it, within limits, and therefore sample received data correctly.
[src:high-speed-serdes/clock-recovery] The term is most often used to describe digital data transmission, in which case the entire signal is suitable for clock recovery.
[src:high-speed-serdes/clock-recovery] For instance, in the case of early 300 bit/s modems, the timing of the signal was recovered from the transitions between the two frequencies used to represent binary 1 and 0.
[src:high-speed-serdes/clock-recovery] As some data might not have any transitions, a long string of zeros for instance, additional bits are added to the signal, the start and stop bits.
[src:high-speed-serdes/clock-recovery] These ensure that there are at least two transitions every 1⁄30 of a second, enough to allow the receiver to accurately set its local oscillator.
[src:high-speed-serdes/clock-recovery] The basic concept is also used in a wider variety of fields, including non-digital uses.
[src:high-speed-serdes/clock-recovery] For instance, the pioneering Wireless Set Number 10 used clock recovery to properly sample the analog pulse-width modulation (PWM) voice signals it carried.
[src:high-speed-serdes/clock-recovery] Another example of this concept is used in color television systems.
[src:high-speed-serdes/clock-recovery] Color information is carried at a very specific frequency that can drift from station to station.
[src:high-speed-serdes/clock-recovery] In order for receivers to accurately match the transmitter's own carrier frequency, the transmitter sends a short burst of the signal in the unused space before the start of a scan line.
[src:high-speed-serdes/clock-recovery] This color burst signal is used to feed a local oscillator in the television, which then uses that local signal to decode the color information in the line.
[src:high-speed-serdes/clock-recovery] In these examples, the concept is known as carrier recovery.
[src:high-speed-serdes/clock-recovery] Some digital data streams, especially high-speed serial data streams (such as the raw stream of data from the magnetic head of a disk drive and serial communication networks such as Ethernet) are sent without an accompanying clock signal.
[src:high-speed-serdes/clock-recovery] The receiver generates a clock from an approximate frequency reference, and then phase-aligns the clock to the transitions in the data stream with a phase-locked loop (PLL).
[src:high-speed-serdes/clock-recovery] This is one method of performing a process commonly known as *clock and data recovery* (CDR).
[src:high-speed-serdes/clock-recovery] Other methods include the use of a delay-locked loop and oversampling of the data stream.
[src:high-speed-serdes/clock-recovery] Oversampling can be done *blind* using multiple phases of a free-running clock to create multiple samples of the input and then selecting the best sample.
[src:high-speed-serdes/clock-recovery] Or, a counter can be used that is driven by a sampling clock running at some multiple of the data stream frequency, with the counter reset on every transition of the data stream and the data stream sampled at some predetermined count.
[src:high-speed-serdes/clock-recovery] These two types of oversampling are sometimes called *spatial* and *time* respectively.
[src:high-speed-serdes/clock-recovery] The best bit error ratio (BER) is obtained when the samples are taken as far away as possible from any data stream transitions.
[src:high-speed-serdes/clock-recovery] In oversampling type CDRs, the signal used to sample the data can be used as the recovered clock.
[src:high-speed-serdes/clock-recovery] Clock recovery is very closely related to the problem of carrier recovery, which is the process of re-creating a phase-locked version of the carrier when a suppressed carrier modulation scheme is used.
[src:high-speed-serdes/clock-recovery] These problems were first addressed in a 1956 paper, which introduced a clock-recovery method now known as the Costas loop.
[src:high-speed-serdes/clock-recovery] Since then many additional methods have been developed.
[src:high-speed-serdes/clock-recovery] In order for this scheme to work, a data stream must transition frequently enough to correct for any drift in the PLL's oscillator.
[src:high-speed-serdes/clock-recovery] The limit for how long a clock-recovery unit can operate without a transition is known as its maximum consecutive identical digits (CID) specification.
[src:high-speed-serdes/clock-recovery] To ensure frequent transitions, some sort of self-clocking signal is used, often a run length limited encoding; 8b/10b encoding is very common, while Manchester encoding serves the same purpose in old revisions of 802.3 local area networks.
[src:high-speed-serdes/equalization-communications] In telecommunication, **equalization** is the reversal of distortion incurred by a signal transmitted through a channel.
[src:high-speed-serdes/equalization-communications] **Equalizers** are used to render the frequency response—for instance of a telephone line—*flat* from end-to-end.
[src:high-speed-serdes/equalization-communications] When a channel has been equalized the frequency domain attributes of the signal at the input are faithfully reproduced at the output.
[src:high-speed-serdes/equalization-communications] Telephones, DSL lines and television cables use equalizers to prepare data signals for transmission.
[src:high-speed-serdes/equalization-communications] Equalizers are critical to the successful operation of electronic systems such as analog broadcast television.
[src:high-speed-serdes/equalization-communications] In this application the actual waveform of the transmitted signal must be preserved, not just its frequency content.
[src:high-speed-serdes/equalization-communications] Equalizing filters must cancel out any group delay and phase delay between different frequency components.
[src:high-speed-serdes/equalization-communications] Early telephone systems used equalization to correct for the reduced level of high frequencies in long cables, typically using Zobel networks.
[src:high-speed-serdes/equalization-communications] These kinds of equalizers can also be used to produce a circuit with a wider bandwidth than the standard telephone band of 300 Hz to 3.4 kHz.
[src:high-speed-serdes/equalization-communications] This was particularly useful for broadcasters who needed "music" quality, not "telephone" quality on landlines carrying program material.
[src:high-speed-serdes/equalization-communications] It is necessary to remove or cancel any loading coils in the line before equalization can be successful.
[src:high-speed-serdes/equalization-communications] A similar approach to audio was taken with television landlines with two important additional complications.
[src:high-speed-serdes/equalization-communications] The first of these is that the television signal is a wide bandwidth covering many more octaves than an audio signal.
[src:high-speed-serdes/equalization-communications] A television equalizer consequently typically requires more filter sections than an audio equalizer.
[src:high-speed-serdes/equalization-communications] To keep this manageable, television equalizer sections were often combined into a single network using ladder topology to form a Cauer equalizer.
[src:high-speed-serdes/equalization-communications] The second issue is that phase equalization is essential for an analog television signal.
[src:high-speed-serdes/equalization-communications] Without it dispersion causes the loss of integrity of the original wave-shape and is seen as smearing of what were originally sharp edges in the picture.
[src:high-speed-serdes/equalization-communications] Picturephone circuits also had equalizers.
[src:high-speed-serdes/equalization-communications] In digital communications, the equalizer's purpose is to reduce intersymbol interference to allow recovery of the transmit symbols.
[src:high-speed-serdes/equalization-communications] It may be a simple linear filter or a complex algorithm.
[src:high-speed-serdes/pulse-amplitude-modulation] Pulse-amplitude modulation is widely used in modulating signal transmission of digital data, with non-baseband applications having been largely replaced by pulse-code modulation, and, more recently, by pulse-position modulation.
[src:high-speed-serdes/pulse-amplitude-modulation] The number of possible pulse amplitudes in analog PAM is theoretically infinite.
[src:high-speed-serdes/pulse-amplitude-modulation] Digital PAM reduces the number of pulse amplitudes to some natural number not less than 3 (PAM-2 would be a simple binary signal and is usually not considered to be PAM).
[src:high-speed-serdes/pulse-amplitude-modulation] Common choices for the number of amplitudes are: 3, 4, 5, 8, 16.
[src:high-speed-serdes/pulse-amplitude-modulation] Some versions of the Ethernet communication standard are an example of PAM usage.
[src:high-speed-serdes/pulse-amplitude-modulation] USB4 Version 2.0 uses PAM-3 signaling for USB4 80 Gbps (USB4 Gen 4×2) and USB4 120 Gbps (USB4 Gen 4 Asymmetric) transmitting 3 bits per 2 clock cycles.
[src:high-speed-serdes/pulse-amplitude-modulation] Higher frequencies require higher bandwidth, which is a significant problem beyond 28 GHz when trying to transmit through copper.
[src:high-speed-serdes/pulse-amplitude-modulation] PAM-4 costs more to implement than earlier NRZ (non return to zero, PAM-2) coding partly because it requires more space in integrated circuits, and is more susceptible to SNR (signal to noise ratio) problems.
[src:high-speed-serdes/pulse-amplitude-modulation] GDDR7 utilizes PAM-3 signaling to achieve speeds of 36 Gbps/pin.
[src:high-speed-serdes/pulse-amplitude-modulation] The higher data transmission rate per cycle compared to NRZ/PAM-2-signaling used by GDDR6 and prior generations improves power efficiency and signal integrity.
[src:high-speed-serdes/pulse-amplitude-modulation] Compared to PAM-4 (GDDR6X), it is less strict on manufacturing equipment.
[src:high-speed-serdes/pulse-amplitude-modulation] PCI Express 6.0 has introduced PAM-4 usage.
[src:high-speed-serdes/pulse-amplitude-modulation] The North American Advanced Television Systems Committee standards for digital television uses a form of PAM to broadcast the data that makes up the television signal.
[src:high-speed-serdes/pulse-amplitude-modulation] This system, known as 8VSB, is based on an eight-level PAM.
[src:high-speed-serdes/pulse-amplitude-modulation] It uses additional processing to suppress one sideband and thus make more efficient use of limited bandwidth.
[src:high-speed-serdes/pulse-amplitude-modulation] Using a single 6 MHz channel allocation, as defined in the previous NTSC analog standard, 8VSB is capable of transmitting 32 Mbit/s.
[src:high-speed-serdes/pulse-amplitude-modulation] After accounting for error-correcting codes and other overhead, the data rate in the signal is 19.39 Mbit/s.
[src:high-speed-serdes/pulse-amplitude-modulation] Unlike the traditional dark-adapted chlorophyll fluorescence measurements, pulse amplitude fluorescence devices allow measuring under ambient light conditions, which made measurements significantly more versatile.
[src:high-speed-serdes/pulse-amplitude-modulation] Pulse-amplitude modulation has also been developed for the control of light-emitting diodes (LEDs), especially for lighting applications.
[src:high-speed-serdes/pulse-amplitude-modulation] Pulse-amplitude modulation LED drivers are able to synchronize pulses across multiple LED channels to enable perfect color matching.
[src:high-speed-serdes/pulse-amplitude-modulation] Due to the inherent nature of PAM in conjunction with the rapid switching speed of LEDs, it is possible to use LED lighting as a means of wireless data transmission at high speed.
[src:high-speed-serdes/serdes] A **Serializer/Deserializer** (**SerDes**) is a pair of functional blocks commonly used in high speed communications to compensate for limited input/output.
[src:high-speed-serdes/serdes] These blocks convert data between serial data and parallel interfaces in each direction.
[src:high-speed-serdes/serdes] The term "SerDes" generically refers to interfaces used in various technologies and applications.
[src:high-speed-serdes/serdes] The primary use of a SerDes is to provide data transmission over a single line or a differential pair in order to minimize the number of I/O pins and interconnects.
[src:high-speed-serdes/serdes] The basic SerDes function is made up of two functional blocks: the Parallel In Serial Out (PISO) block (a.k.a.
[src:high-speed-serdes/serdes] Parallel-to-Serial converter) and the Serial In Parallel Out (SIPO) block (a.k.a.
[src:high-speed-serdes/serdes] There are 4 different SerDes architectures: (1) Parallel clock SerDes, (2) Embedded clock SerDes, (3) 8b/10b SerDes, (4) Bit interleaved SerDes.
[src:high-speed-serdes/serdes] The PISO (Parallel Input, Serial Output) block typically has a parallel clock input, a set of data input lines, and input data latches.
[src:high-speed-serdes/serdes] It may use an internal or external phase-locked loop (PLL) to multiply the incoming parallel clock up to the serial frequency.
[src:high-speed-serdes/serdes] The simplest form of the PISO has a single shift register that receives the parallel data once per parallel clock, and shifts it out at the higher serial clock rate.
[src:high-speed-serdes/serdes] Implementations may also make use of a double-buffered register to avoid metastability when transferring data between clock domains.
[src:high-speed-serdes/serdes] The SIPO (Serial Input, Parallel Output) block typically has a receive clock output, a set of data output lines and output data latches.
[src:high-speed-serdes/serdes] The receive clock may have been recovered from the data by the serial clock recovery technique.
[src:high-speed-serdes/serdes] However, SerDes which do not transmit a clock use reference clock to lock the PLL to the correct Tx frequency, avoiding low harmonic frequencies present in the data stream.
[src:high-speed-serdes/serdes] The SIPO block then divides the incoming clock down to the parallel rate.
[src:high-speed-serdes/serdes] Implementations typically have two registers connected as a double buffer.
[src:high-speed-serdes/serdes] One register is used to clock in the serial stream, and the other is used to hold the data for the slower, parallel side.
[src:high-speed-serdes/serdes] Some types of SerDes include encoding/decoding blocks.
[src:high-speed-serdes/serdes] The purpose of this encoding/decoding is typically to place at least statistical bounds on the rate of signal transitions to allow for easier clock recovery in the receiver, to provide framing, and to provide DC balance.
[src:high-speed-serdes/serdes] Parallel clock SerDes is normally used to serialize a parallel bus input along with data address & control signals.
[src:high-speed-serdes/serdes] The serialized stream is sent along with a reference clock.
[src:high-speed-serdes/serdes] The clock jitter tolerance at the serializer is 5–10 ps rms.
[src:high-speed-serdes/serdes] An embedded clock SerDes serializes data and clock into a single stream.
[src:high-speed-serdes/serdes] One cycle of clock signal is transmitted first, followed by the data bit stream; this creates a periodic rising edge at the start of the data bit stream.
[src:high-speed-serdes/serdes] As the clock is explicitly embedded and can be recovered from the bit stream, the serializer (transmitter) clock jitter tolerance is relaxed to 80–120 ps rms, while the reference clock disparity at the deserializer can be ±50,000 ppm (i.e.
[src:high-speed-serdes/serdes] 8b/10b SerDes maps each data byte to a 10-bit code before serializing the data.
[src:high-speed-serdes/serdes] The deserializer uses the reference clock to monitor the recovered clock from the bit stream.
[src:high-speed-serdes/serdes] As the clock information is synthesized into the data bit stream, rather than explicitly embedding it, the serializer (transmitter) clock jitter tolerance is to 5–10 ps rms and the reference clock disparity at the deserializer is ±100 ppm.
[src:high-speed-serdes/serdes] A common coding scheme used with SerDes is 8b/10b encoding.
[src:high-speed-serdes/serdes] This supports DC-balance, provides framing, and guarantees frequent transitions, allowing a receiver to extract the embedded clock.
[src:high-speed-serdes/serdes] The control codes allow framing, typically on the start of a packet.
[src:high-speed-serdes/serdes] The typical 8b/10b SerDes parallel side interfaces have one clock line, one control line and 8 data lines.
[src:high-speed-serdes/serdes] Such serializer-plus-8b/10b encoder, and deserializer-plus-decoder blocks are defined in the Gigabit Ethernet specification.
[src:high-speed-serdes/serdes] Another common coding scheme used with SerDes is 64b/66b encoding.
[src:high-speed-serdes/serdes] This scheme statistically delivers DC-balance and transitions through the use of a scrambler.
[src:high-speed-serdes/serdes] Framing is delivered through the deterministic transitions of the added framing bits.
[src:high-speed-serdes/serdes] Such serializer-plus-64b/66b encoder and deserializer-plus-decoder blocks are defined in the 10 Gigabit Ethernet specification.
[src:high-speed-serdes/serdes] The transmit side comprises a 64b/66b encoder, a scrambler, and a gearbox that converts the 66b signal to a 16-bit interface.
[src:high-speed-serdes/serdes] Another serializer then converts this 16-bit interface into a fully serial signal.
[src:high-speed-serdes/serdes] Bit interleaved SerDes multiplexes several slower serial data streams into faster serial streams, and the receiver demultiplexes the faster bitstreams back to slower streams.
[src:high-speed-serdes/serdes] The Optical Internetworking Forum (OIF) has published the Common Electrical I/O (CEI) Interoperability Agreements (IAs), that have defined six generations of the electrical interface of SerDes, at 3.125, 6, 10, 28, 56 and 112 Gb/s.
[src:high-speed-serdes/serdes] The OIF has announced new projects at 224 Gb/s.
[src:high-speed-serdes/serdes] The OIF also published three earlier generations of electrical interfaces.
[src:high-speed-serdes/serdes] These IAs have been adopted or adapted or have influenced high speed electrical interfaces defined by IEEE 802.3, Infiniband, RapidIO, Fibre Channel and numerous others.
